<TITLE> Malaysia bans Bangladeshi workers, Dhaka upset </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 KUALA LUMPUR, Oct 4 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Malaysia has banned imports of Bangladeshi workers into the country after hundreds of them were stranded at an airport because their employers failed to collect them promptly, a newspaper said on Thursday. But the move, which took immediate effect, drew a sharp protest from the employers and the Bangladeshi government, with Dhaka calling it as "disheartening." "We hope it is only for weeks, not months or years," M. Khairuzzaman, the Bangladeshi ambassador to Malaysia, told the Star newspaper. "If there are loopholes in the system, lets plug it." "The government is always playing hot and cold," said an official at the Malaysian Employers' Federation. "This is causing havoc to our planning. This is not good in terms of long-term investment." Fast-industrialising Malaysia has been a magnet for foreign workers to help fill menial jobs that Malaysians shun. It has 2.7 million legal foreign workers, mainly from Indonesia. Hundreds of thousands more are working illegally. Home Minister Radzi Sheikh Ahmad announced the ban on Wednesday following "too many problems" relating to hiring Bangladeshis. He did not elaborate. The government had placed a similar restriction in 1999 but lifted the ban last year by approving an initial intake of 300,000 workers. About 200,000 of them have arrived into the count
